<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Tiles pixels 2x, 4x (or more) - HD remaking of NES games]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=9029&amp;p=98100#p98100"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">joabfarias wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />It means that a version of MegaMan in a emulator that works like HiSMS would be a little bit boring to make...<br />Every single animation frame would have to be done a dozen times or more.<br /></div><br />There are two ways to handle this:<br /><ol style="list-style-type: lower-alpha"><li>Have the emulator always use a constant palette that includes light, medium, and dark versions of all three colors in a particular sprite palette, as well as black, gray, and white. </li><li>Use the palette changes as an opportunity to add unique detailing to Mega Man's sprite for each state. </li></ol><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />How dows HiSMS work when the sprite is partially hidden (like when Alex is behind bushes, for example)?<br /></div><br />I imagine that most games just use the tiles' priority bits. (The SMS does it backward compared to the NES. On the SMS, priority is assigned to tiles, not sprites.) Games that perform occlusion in software using CHR RAM updates, like Solstice for NES, would have a bigger problem.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Tue Aug 14, 2012 5:14 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
